I think of it less as a ladder and more as a living spiral. Information doesn’t simply climb upward once—it loops, gets tested, discarded, refined, and sometimes returns to an earlier stage in a richer form.

One possible cycle looks like this:

Signal
   ↓
Attention
   ↓
Perception
   ↓
Thought
   ↓
Question
   ↓
Hypothesis
   ↓
Belief (provisional commitment)
   ↓
Action / Experiment
   ↓
Evidence
   ↓
Knowledge
   ↓
Understanding
   ↓
Judgment
   ↓
Wisdom
   ↓
Teaching / Creation
   ↓
Transmission
   ↓
Another mind...

But the interesting part is the feedback loops.

A single experience can shatter a belief and send you back to thought.

Knowledge can expose flaws in perception.

Wisdom can change what you pay attention to in the first place.

So the spiral doesn’t merely go upward—it reshapes its own entrance.

I would distinguish the stages this way:

* Signal — raw difference in the world.
* Information — signal given structure.
* Thought — internal manipulation of information.
* Belief — information granted trust.
* Knowledge — belief repeatedly surviving contact with evidence.
* Understanding — seeing relationships among pieces of knowledge.
* Wisdom — knowing when, where, why, and whether to apply understanding.
* Judgment — wisdom acting under uncertainty.
* Legacy — wisdom encoded outside oneself.

The transfer between people is also transformative.

Reality
   ↓
Experience
   ↓
Mind A
   ↓
Language
   ↓
Book / Speech / Art / Code
   ↓
Mind B
   ↓
Reconstruction

Nothing is copied exactly.

Each transfer is a reconstruction.

Meaning survives not because the symbols are identical, but because the receiver rebuilds a sufficiently similar internal structure. This aligns closely with your Pantheon theme that communication is constrained reconstruction rather than literal transmission.

There’s another spiral that runs underneath:

Notice
Think
Believe
Test
Know
Doubt
Refine
Know Better
Teach
Be Challenged
Learn Again

Notice that doubt isn’t the opposite of knowledge—it’s one of its maintenance mechanisms. Healthy knowledge keeps looping through doubt to remain calibrated.

The deepest insight, though, may be this:

Thought is movement.
Belief is stabilization.
Knowledge is validated stabilization.
Understanding is integration.
Wisdom is adaptive application.
Teaching is externalization.
Culture is distributed memory.
History is long-term memory.
Evolution is memory written into matter.

From that perspective, the entire universe can be viewed as a hierarchy of memory systems. Atoms preserve physical laws. DNA preserves biological adaptations. Brains preserve experiences. Languages preserve shared concepts. Libraries preserve civilizations. Scientific theories preserve tested explanations. Each layer stores patterns discovered by the layer below and passes them forward, where they are tested, modified, and re-encoded.

The spiral isn’t just ascending—it’s compressing and transmitting. Every loop attempts to preserve what proved useful while remaining open to revision. That’s what allows information to become enduring knowledge rather than static dogma.